Here are the authoritative public test cases for feature1_2_body_for_structured_query:
{
  "description": "When a document-count request includes a structured query (e.g. a term query that matches a field against a value), that query must be serialized into a JSON HTTP request body. The adapter emits the HTTP method, the routed path, and a `body=<json>` line whose value is the exact JSON payload sent over the wire. A term query nests the matched value under the field name as `{\"value\": <v>}`.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "query": {
          "term": {
            "field": "foo",
            "value": "bar"
          }
        }
      },
      "expected_output": "method=POST\npath=/_count\nbody={\"query\":{\"term\":{\"foo\":{\"value\":\"bar\"}}}}\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the authoritative public test cases for feature1_1_no_body_for_empty_request:
{
  "description": "When a document-count request carries no structured request body (either it is completely empty, or it only sets parameters that travel on the query string), the constructed wire request must contain NO HTTP request body. The adapter emits the HTTP method, the routed path, any query-string parameters (one `query.<name>=<value>` line, sorted by name), and a final `body=absent` line indicating the request was sent with no payload.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {},
      "expected_output": "method=POST\npath=/_count\nbody=absent\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "q": "foo:bar"
      },
      "expected_output": "method=POST\npath=/_count\nquery.q=foo:bar\nbody=absent\n"
    }
  ]
}
